1) List and explain the main features of Java.
-->automatic memory management (garbage collection), secure architecture, multithreading for concurrent tasks, 
    and high performance enabled by the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) and Just-in-Time (JIT) compiler.

2) What does “Platform Independent” mean in Java?
--> a Java program can be written and compiled on one operating system (platform) and its resulting compiled
    code (bytecode) can be executed on any other platform without modification or recompilation, provided that the 
    target system has a compatible Java Virtual Machine (JVM) installed.

3) What is meant by “Object-Oriented” in Java?
-->In Java, "Object-Oriented" refers to the programming paradigm that structures software design
    around objects, which are instances of classes that bundle together related data (fields) and behaviors (methods).

4) What is the importance of “Robustness” in Java?
-->Robustness in Java ensures applications are reliable, stable, and capable of handling unexpected errors without crashing.

5) What makes Java “Secure”?
-->due to use of bytecode verification and absence of pointer and use features like sandbox in java make it secure
Java is considered a highly secure language due to its design, which incorporates several 
    built-in security mechanisms at both the language and runtime levels.

6) Explain the feature “Portable” in Java.
-->The "Portable" feature in Java refers to its ability to run the same compiled program on any 
    operating system or hardware architecture that has a compatible Java Virtual Machine (JVM

) installed,       
    without needing to recompile the code. This principle is famously summarized by the motto "Write Once, Run Anywhere" (WORA). 

7) How does Java achieve “Multithreading”?
-->Java achieves multithreading by allowing multiple threads (lightweight processes) to run concurrently using the Thread class and
    Runnable interface.
Java achieves multithreading through built-in language support and a rich set of APIs that enable the concurrent execution of
    multiple threads within a single program. This allows applications to perform multiple tasks simultaneously, maximizing CPU 
    utilization and improving responsiveness

8) What is “Dynamic” in Java?
-->“Dynamic” in Java means that certain decisions (like method execution or memory allocation) are made at runtime instead of compile time.
    In Java, "dynamic" is a term generally used to refer to operations or behaviors that are resolved during runtime, rather than at compile time.

9) Explain “Distributed” and how Java supports distributed systems.
-->A distributed system is a collection of independent computers (nodes) that work together and appear to users as a single, unified system. 

10) How does Java achieve “Architecture Neutrality”?
--> Java achieves Architecture Neutrality through its two-stage compilation process and the standardization of its execution environment,
    ensuring that code behaves identically across different hardware and software systems. 
    java achieves "Architecture Neutrality" through the use of bytecode and the Java Virtual Machine (JVM), which together enable its "Write Once, Run Anywhere" (WORA) principle. 

11) What does “Compiled and Interpreted” mean in Java?
-->In Java, the phrase "compiled and interpreted" refers to its two-stage execution process, a hybrid approach designed to
    provide both the performance benefits of a compiled language and the portability of an interpreted one.


12) How does automatic garbage collection contribute to reliability?
-->Automatic garbage collection (GC) improves software reliability by automatically reclaiming unused memory, which prevents memory leaks, 
    dangling pointers, and memory exhaustion that cause application crashes. 

13) What is bytecode, and why is it important?
-->Bytecode is an intermediate, platform-independent representation of source code generated by a compiler (e.g., javac for Java) 
    rather than direct machine code. It acts as a low-level, binary language executed by a virtual machine—like the Java Virtual
    Machine (JVM)—enabling "Write Once, Run Anywhere" portability across different hardware architectures. 


14) Why is Java often called “Write Once, Run Anywhere”?
-->Java is called "Write Once, Run Anywhere" (WORA) because code compiled on one platform (e.g., Windows) can run on any other platform (e.g., Linux, macOS) without modification. 

15) How do features like JIT improve Java’s performance?
-->The Just-In-Time (JIT) compiler significantly improves Java performance by converting platform-independent bytecode into optimized, native machine code during program execution. 

